	<body>
		<nav class="site-nav" aria-label="Section navigation">
			<a href="/">&larr; nrbts.world</a>
		</nav>

		<main class="content">
			<section class="writing-hero">
				<p class="mono eyebrow">WRITING</p>
				<h1>Selected running pieces</h1>
				<p class="hero-sub">Drawn from a personal running journal.</p>
			</section>

			<section class="essays">
				<article class="essay panel-body">
					<p class="essay-meta mono">Personal essay &middot; marathon race report</p>
					<h2>A Marathon Every Ten Years</h2>
					<div class="essay-body">
						<p>
							The last time I'd run a marathon, it was 2015 and I was in Berlin,
							chasing a number that belonged to my dad. He'd run Zurich once,
							years before, and left behind a time that sat in the family like a
							small unpaid debt. So I trained, I went out, and I beat it —
							3:40:59 — and then I didn't run another marathon for ten years.
						</p>
						<p>
							That's not a plan you set out to make. It's the kind of thing you
							notice in hindsight and decide to call a tradition. One marathon a
							decade: enough time to forget exactly how much the last six miles
							hurt, which is, as far as I can tell, the only condition under which
							anyone signs up again.
						</p>
						<p>
							So: Mesa, Arizona, February, ten years later. The buses leave Sloan
							Park at four in the morning and climb into the desert dark toward a
							start line you can't see yet. They let you off below the big white
							Phoenix sign on Usery Mountain, into a cold that's dry and sourceless
							and gone the second the sun clears the ridge. Two thousand of us
							stand around in space blankets, breathing steam. I'd come with one
							number in my head — not my dad's this time, but my own, the one my
							ten-years-younger self had posted in Berlin. The question of the day
							was whether who I am now could beat who I was then.
						</p>
						<p>
							Mesa is built for exactly that kind of question: a thousand feet of
							net downhill, point to point, one of the fastest courses in the
							country. Which sounds like a gift, and is also the trap. The opening
							miles drop hard and clean, and two forces conspire to make you spend
							too much too soon — gravity, which hands you a quicker stride than
							you've earned, and adrenaline, the start-line hype that catapults the
							whole field early. Both had to be worked against, consciously, the
							entire first stretch. A lot of those early miles went not into
							running fast but into controlling the pace. I spent the prettiest
							part of the course mostly talking myself into patience and watching
							the sky work through its gradients of blue and orange as the sun came
							up.
						</p>
						<p>
							I hadn't planned to run with a pacer at all, figuring I'd run my own
							race by feel. But the first few kilometers came easy — easier than
							the plan — and somewhere in there I made a decision I didn't
							overthink: I moved up and tucked in behind the 3:40 pacer.
						</p>
						<p>
							For a long while it was almost social. That early in a marathon
							everyone's still laughing, trading the small talk you use to work out
							who you're spending the morning with. Our pacer had run Boston not
							long before — which, if you know what those qualifying times ask of
							you, is no small thing — a personal dream come true for her. We got
							along and kept chatting, kilometer after kilometer. I barely looked
							at my watch, partly because I trusted her to hold the line, and
							partly because I know myself: too much focus on the numbers on my
							wrist can ruin a whole race day.
						</p>
						<p>
							We are at kilometer 35 and I see her checking her watch, followed by
							a quick look of confusion and then words you never want to hear your
							pacer say: "oops — looks like we're a bit behind," which is a small
							sentence with a large meaning: time to make up, now, at this stage of
							the race. By then the group had thinned to almost nothing — the
							pacer, me, maybe three others still hanging on while the rest had
							either surged off or slipped back into the field. She pushed the
							pace. I told my body to keep up. My muscles went from burning like a
							fire to burning like the sun, and the whole thing narrowed to a
							singular thought and conviction: do not let this time slip away.
							That's what a marathon becomes this far in — not a question of
							physical energy anymore but of will, of how much discomfort you're
							willing to accept. And there's a trick the mind plays this late: it
							feels like the finish is being decided right now, that every second
							you're willing to hurt in the last three K claws back real time.
							It's mostly a lie — the clock is won earlier, at a steadier pace —
							but the feeling comes with its own adrenaline, and I used it. I ran
							as if everything hung on the next few minutes, and that was enough to
							push me off the front of the pack.
						</p>
						<p>
							3:39:39. Eighty seconds faster than Berlin — eighty seconds faster
							than a version of me a decade younger. It's not a large margin.
							Stretched across ten years it's almost nothing, and that's exactly
							the point: you get one honest rematch with your younger self every
							ten years, and this time the older one took it.
						</p>
					</div>
				</article>

				<article class="essay panel-body">
					<p class="essay-meta mono">Personal essay &middot; trail race story</p>
					<h2>Took a Spill?</h2>
					<div class="essay-body">
						<p>
							Mt. Hood was my first trail race, and I signed up to answer the basic
							question: could I finish it unharmed? Roads I understood. Roads are a
							known quantity — you pick a pace and you become one with it. Trails
							were a rumor I'd heard about from more adventurous people.
						</p>
						<p>
							It turns out you don't run a trail so much as negotiate with it.
							Extended climbs, footing that changes every stride, a course that
							keeps asking questions your road legs have never had to answer. The
							trail does not ask for your undivided attention, it demands it. And
							if it does, do yourself a favor and take note of it.
						</p>
						<p>
							I did not follow this advice, tripped over a tree root and covered
							myself in crimson soil from top to bottom for the rest of the race.
						</p>
						<p>
							I carried this look to the next aid station, where a volunteer took
							one look at me, grinned, and said, "Took a spill?" — while handing me
							a cup of water. I couldn't tell you whether the pun was intended.
							What I understood in that moment, watching him already turn to the
							next dust-covered mess behind me, was that this happens to everyone.
							The falling isn't a sign you don't belong out here. The falling is
							the membership fee.
						</p>
					</div>
				</article>

				<article class="essay panel-body">
					<p class="essay-meta mono">Product review &middot; Nike Pegasus Trail 5 GTX</p>
					<h2>Nike Pegasus Trail 5 GTX — A Review</h2>
					<div class="essay-body">
						<p>
							I've put these through the kind of terrain they were arguably built
							for and definitely tested by: the rock, dust, and weather of Mount
							St. Helens, where I catch my toes on things for a living.
						</p>
						<p>
							Start with the ride, because it surprised me. The forefoot has more
							bounce than its thickness suggests — Nike's ReactX foam — and enough
							feel that you never lose the ground. That balance matters more on
							trail than on road: too soft and you're guessing where the rock is;
							here you can read the terrain and commit to your footing without
							trust issues.
						</p>
						<p>
							The upper is the other quiet strength. The structured panels along
							the side walls lock the foot down as the lacing cinches, and they
							hold that shape through side-loading and off-camber steps. No
							internal sliding, which on technical ground is the difference between
							trusting a foot placement and hedging it. The built-in gaiter at the
							collar is close to ideal for a place like St. Helens and its ground
							conditions.
						</p>
						<p>
							The outsole — Nike All Terrain Compound — has enough grip for most of
							what I throw at it. Dry rock, dust, gravel, damp singletrack: all
							fine. The honest limits show up in deep mud, snow, and genuinely
							heavy rain.
						</p>
						<p>
							Two real gripes. Once the GORE-TEX upper is properly soaked, it is
							slow — so slow — to dry. This becomes a genuine problem on multi-day
							efforts, when the shoe never gets a real chance to come back. Second,
							and relatedly: I wish Nike had put Vibram on the bottom. The ATC
							compound is good; Vibram, on terrain this serious, would have been
							the thing that let me stop thinking about the outsole altogether.
						</p>
						<p>
							Verdict: a confident, protective, well-locked-in trail shoe that's
							stronger on rock and dust than in mud and snow, and better across one
							long day than a wet multi-day. For most of what I do, it's a shoe I
							keep reaching for — it has even seen some PCT this year.
						</p>
					</div>
				</article>
			</section>

